  "prompt": "Complete an orbital diagram for scandium (Sc).?",
  "response": "To complete an orbital diagram for scandium (Sc), first, we need to know its electron configuration. Scandium has an atomic number of 21, which means it has 21 electrons. The electron configuration for scandium is:\n\n1s\u00b2 2s\u00b2 2p\u2076 3s\u00b2 3p\u2076 3d\u00b9 4s\u00b2\n\nTo represent this in an orbital diagram, we will show the distribution of these electrons in the respective orbitals. Below is a visual representation of the orbital diagram for scandium:\n\n```\n1s: \u2191\u2193\n2s: \u2191\u2193\n2p: \u2191\u2193 \u2191\u2193 \u2191\u2193\n3s: \u2191\u2193\n3p: \u2191\u2193 \u2191\u2193 \u2191\u2193\n3d: \u2191   \u2191   \u2191   \u2191   \u2191\n4s: \u2191\u2193\n```\n\n### Explanation:\n- **1s orbital** has 2 electrons (\u2191\u2193).\n- **2s orbital** has 2 electrons (\u2191\u2193).\n- **2p orbitals** (three of them) have 6 electrons distributed (\u2191\u2193 for each orbital).\n- **3s orbital** has 2 electrons (\u2191\u2193).\n- **3p orbitals** have 6 electrons distributed (\u2191\u2193 for each orbital).\n- **3d orbitals** have 1 electron (represented as \u2191 in one of the five orbitals).\n- **4s orbital** has 2 electrons (\u2191\u2193).\n\nIn summary, scandium's electrons fill the orbitals according to the Aufbau principle, Hund's rule, and the Pauli exclusion principle.",
